e kids will bring in a bit more $ from the state - but not enough to expand the schools, hire more teachers, and keep the numbers in the classroom below 25.  Meanwhile, valuable programs are cut and sports get bigger (our 5000 kid high school just added a zillion dollar giant state of the art workout room for the athletes - I mean, seriously, we're not even in TX!). Teachers are forced to teach special needs kids w/no training.  Parents insist their kids are always right and must get A's for their self esteem.  Programs exist that allow kids to misspell words and get math problems wrong (as long as they are thinking and can explain how they got their wrong answer, it's ok).  If I didn't live near good schools, I'd do private! "/><type4:DocumentMetaData xmi:id="13" sofa="1" begin="0" end="1043" language="en" documentId="3439" isLastSegment="false"/><types:WebArgumentMetadata xmi:id="24" sofa="1" begin="0" end="0" author="bookaday19" date="Aug 29, 2013 7:11PM" docType="artcomment" origUrl="http://living.msn.com/family-parenting/the-family-room-blog-post?post=ab228ffc-1e99-4b37-a7b8-0b6a4c3fb240" topic="public-private-schools" thumbsUp="15" thumbsDown="0" origId="3439" notes="" title="Is it wrong to send kids to private school?"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="39" sofa="1" begin="0" end="1043"/><cas:View sofa="1" members="13 24 39"/></xmi:XMI>